n insulin action is impaired?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glycogenesis and gluconeogenesis","Glycogenolysis and glycolysis","Glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis","Glycogenesis and glycolysis","Glycolysis and lipolysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen insulin action is impaired, the liver increases \u003Cstrong\u003Eglycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E. Insulin normally inhibits these processes, promoting glycogen storage and glucose uptake instead. Without effective insulin action, the liver breaks down glycogen into glucose and produces glucose from non-carbohydrate sources, contributing to hyperglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Impaired insulin action in the liver leads to increased glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.","Insulin normally inhibits glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis, promoting glycogen storage and glucose uptake."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. Hoboken: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020;10(4):174-188.","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, et al. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020;21(17):6275.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 79; pg. 976"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17914"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:16:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:16:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id